What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113,937 loan records in the dataset with 81 features. Most variables are numeric in nature, some are nominal variables, such as Occupation, Employment Status and some are Boolean variables regarding questions like whether borrower is homeowner, whether borrower's income verifiable, whether borrower is currently in a group.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what factors affect a loans outcome status, and what affects the borrowers APR or interest rate in the dataset.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • I expect that income, loan amount and credit score will affect loan's outcome status: individuals that have a smaller loan, higher income or higher credit scor are more likely to clear off loans. There might be other variables related, such as whether borrower is homeowner, debt to income ratio,
  • Regarding borrower's interest rate, borrower's income is supposed to be related. The lower the borrower's income, the higher the loan interest rate.

Loan Status have 12 categories, namely Current, Completed, Chargedoff, Defaulted, Past Due (1-15 days), Past Due (31-60 days), Past Due (61-90 days), Past Due (91-120 days), Past Due (16-30 days), FinalPaymentInProgress, Past Due (>120 days), Cancelled. These data will be classified into three general groups: Current, Completed and Defaulted.

Completed loans, loans with final payment in progress and loans regarding Past Due are defined as Completed, considering that investors had no monetary loss. Loans that are Chargedoff and Defaulted are grouped together as Defaulted because investors lost their money. Cancelled data will be deleted as they cannot provide infomation for this analysis. These adjustments are shown through a new variable 'Status'.

# Get index of ordered series
status_order = status_count.index

# Returns the sum of all not-null values in `Status` column
n_loans = status_count.sum()

# Return the highest frequency in the `Status` column
max_loan_count = status_count[0]

# Return the maximum proportion, or in other words, 
# compute the length of the longest bar in terms of the proportion
max_loan_prop = max_loan_count / n_loans

# Use numpy.arange() function to produce a set of evenly spaced proportioned values 
tick_props = np.arange(0, max_loan_prop, 0.1)
# Set tick labels. 
tick_names = ['{:0.2f}'.format(v) for v in tick_props]

# Set seaborn in single color. Choose the first tuple of RGB colors
base_color = sns.color_palette()[0]

# Plot the proportions
sns.countplot(data=df_clean,y='Status', color=base_color,order=status_order);
plt.xticks(tick_props * n_loans, tick_names)
plt.xlabel('proportion');

# Logic to print the proportion text on the bars
for i in range (status_count.shape[0]):
    # Remember, type_counts contains the frequency of unique values in the `type` column in decreasing order.
    count = status_count[i]
    # Convert count into a percentage, and then into string
    pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_loans)
    # Print the string value on the bar. 
    # Read more about the arguments of text() function [here](https://matplotlib.org/3.1.1/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.text.html)
    plt.text(count+1, i, pct_string, va='center')

Among 113061 records, most loans are still in process (nearly 50%), 35.7% of records have been completed and 15% of loans are defaulted.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • In terms of the listing categories, the previous data used numbers. I changed it to names for better understanding.
  • Regarding the loan status, there were so many types and I redefined it into three groups: Current, Completed and Defaulted.
  • Credit score is presented by two variables CreditScoreRangeUpper and CreditScoreRangeLower. The range difference is 19 for each record, so a 'CreditScore' is generated based on the average of upper and lower variables.
  • The StatedMonthlyIncome variable took on a large range of values, so I looked at the data using a log transform. Under the transformation, the income has a normal distribution.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • There's duplicated data with different ProsperScore. As there's no futher infomation to revise the dataset and this variable could be represented by ProsperRating, I decide to drop this variable and then drop the duplicated.
  • There are 590 entries without credit score range. As it's an importent variable, these data were dropped. Besides, 133 borrowers have a credit score of 9.5. As 9.5 is far away from the main part of the distribution (the record higher than 9.5 is 360+), these records will be removed.
  • There are 10 records in which the borrowers earn 160,000 dollars monthly. They were removed as outliers, considering they are far away from the main distributions.
  • Data with debt-to-income ratio of 10.01 were removed as outliers.
  • Two records have have extreme high inquiries (97 and 105), which were removed as outliers.
  • There's weired monthly payment in the data (paying 0-20 dollars monthly), which needed further information. Therefore, this variable was dropped and will not be analysed.
